  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work titled \"A cell type-aware framework for nominating non-coding variants in Mendelian regulatory disorders\" has successfully transitioned from preprint on medRxiv to a peer-reviewed publication in Nature, demonstrating its significant contribution to the field. This research addresses critical challenges in identifying non-coding variants linked to Mendelian disorders through a novel framework.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This study presents a cell type-aware framework aimed at improving the nomination of non-coding variants implicated in Mendelian regulatory disorders. Published in the high-impact journal Nature, this work has garnered nine citations since its initial sharing on medRxiv, reflecting its relevance and resonance in the academic community.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research has received backing from esteemed institutions, including the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Boston Children's Hospital, and the Broad Institute. Such institutional support underscores the credibility and scientific rigor behind the study, suggesting a robust collaborative effort that spans both biomedical and computational perspectives.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although the study has not generated public discourse on platforms like Reddit or Wikipedia, its scholarly impact is evidenced by its citations. The nine citations of the preprint, alongside the subsequent publication's eight citations, indicate ongoing engagement and utilization within the research community, supporting its role as a foundational output in advancing understanding of Mendelian disorders.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Furthermore, this work highlights a commitment to open science through its early sharing on medRxiv, reflecting an intention to stimulate immediate academic dialogue before formal publication. The successful transition from a preprint to a rigorously reviewed article exhibits the significance of rapid dissemination and critical peer evaluation in scientific advancement.</p>",
